  <p>
    The difference becomes obvious once plants are fully grown.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where DIY Connections Start to Fail</h2>

  <p>
    Simple lashings and ties often look secure at first, but they rely on tension rather than structure.
  </p>

  <p>
    Over time:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>knots loosen</li>
    <li>materials stretch</li>
    <li>poles shift unevenly</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This leads to leaning or unstable teepees — especially after rain or wind.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Simple Connectors Are Still Fine</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>short growing seasons</strong></li>
    <li><strong>lightly loaded plants</strong></li>
    <li><strong>temporary or experimental setups</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If the structure doesn’t need to last long or carry much weight, simpler methods can work.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Planning for Setup, Not Load</h3>
  <p>
    The structure needs to handle mature plants, not empty poles.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Flexible Connections</h3>
  <p>
    Movement increases over time, not decreases.
  </p>

  <h3>Ignoring Wind Exposure</h3>
  <p>
    Teepees act like sails once vines fill in.
  </p>

  <h3>Underestimating Plant Weight</h3>
  <p>
    Fruit adds more load than expected.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into a Cucumber Growing System</h2>

  <p>
    The connector is the anchor point of the entire trellis. If it fails, the rest of the system doesn’t matter.
  </p>

  <p>
    A stable teepee improves airflow, makes harvesting easier, and keeps plants off the ground.
  </p>

